{
  "unitNumber": 5,
  "text": {
    "title": "Present Tense of Verbs",
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Use of the Present Tense",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "5.01",
            "content": "The present tense (or simply ‘the present’) is used to state that an action is occurring at the present time. It corresponds basically to the English simple present (‘I eat’) and present continuous (‘I am eating’):",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["**Mio padre lavora per la BBC.**", "My father works for the BBC."],
                ["**Mio padre lavora in giardino.**", "My father’s working in the garden."],
                ["**Di solito guardo la televisione.**", "Normally I watch TV."],
                ["**Stasera guardo la televisione.**", "I’m watching TV this evening."],
                ["**Non guardo la televisione.**", "I don’t watch TV."],
                ["**Perché non guardi la televisione?**", "Why don’t you watch TV?"],
                ["**Stasera non guardo la televisione.**", "I’m not watching TV this evening."],
                ["**Perché non guardi la televisione stasera?**", "Why aren’t you watching TV this evening?"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "5.02",
            "content": "The present can also be used to refer to the future, either the near future or one that is considered fairly certain:",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["**Il treno parte fra cinque minuti.**", "The train leaves/is leaving in five minutes."],
                ["**Parto domani.**", "I leave/I am leaving tomorrow."],
                ["**Domani mattina porto Luca alla stazione.**", "Tomorrow morning I’ll take/I’m taking/I’m going to take Luca to the station."],
                ["**L’estate prossima lavoro con mio zio.**", "Next summer I’ll work/I’m working/going to work with my uncle."]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "5.03",
            "content": "The present is also used to refer to an action which started in the past and is still going on; here, it corresponds to the English present perfect:",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["**Lavoriamo qui da un mese.**", "We’ve been working here for a month."],
                ["**Mio cugino abita a Roma da tre anni.**", "My cousin’s lived/been living in Rome for three years."],
                ["**Conosco Giulia da tre anni.**", "I have known Giulia for three years."],
                ["**Non vedo Dario da mesi.**", "I haven’t seen Dario for months."]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "The Forms of the Present Tense",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "5.04",
            "content": "Italian verbs are divided into three main groups, the conjugations. The conjugation a verb belongs to is determined by the ending of its infinitive:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["First conjugation", "Second conjugation", "Third conjugation"],
              "rows": [
                ["**-are**", "**-ere**", "**-ire**"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "The forms of the present depend on which conjugation the verb belongs to. The present is formed by changing the ending of the infinitive, as follows:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Person", "Singular", "Infinitive in **-are**", "Infinitive in **-ere**", "Infinitive in **-ire**"],
              "rows": [
                ["1st", "(io)", "**-o**", "**-o**", "**(-isc)-o**"],
                ["2nd", "(tu)", "**-i**", "**-i**", "**(-isc)-i**"],
                ["3rd", "(lui/lei)", "**-a**", "**-e**", "**(-isc)-e**"],
                ["", "Plural", "", "", ""],
                ["1st Plural", "(noi)", "**-iamo**", "**-iamo**", "**-iamo**"],
                ["2nd Plural", "(voi)", "**-ate**", "**-ete**", "**-ite**"],
                ["3rd Plural", "(loro)", "**-ano**", "**-ono**", "**(-isc)-ono**"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "5.05",
            "content": "Regular verbs in **-are** are conjugated as follows:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Endings", "", "**Parlare**", "To speak/talk"],
              "rows": [
                ["-o", "(io)",  "**parlo**", "I speak"],
                ["-i", "(tu)",  "**parli**", "you speak"],
                ["-a", "(lui/lei)",  "**parla**", "he/she/it speaks"],
                ["-iamo", "(noi)",  "**parliamo**", "we speak"],
                ["-ate", "(voi)",  "**parlate**", "you speak"],
                ["-ano", "(loro)", "**parlano**", "they speak"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "* As we saw in Unit 4, the subject pronoun is normally omitted in the conjugation of Italian verbs.",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["**Andrea e Carla lavorano in Italia.**", "Andrea and Carla work in Italy."],
                ["**Parlo italiano.* **", "I speak Italian."],
                ["**Parlate molto!* **", "You talk a lot!"],
                ["**Abitiamo a Genova.* **", "We live in Genoa."]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "5.06",
            "content": "Verbs ending in -care and -gare (first conjugation) add h before the endings of the second person singular (-i) and the first person plural (-iamo) in order to keep the hard sound of c and g:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["", "Cercare", "To look for", "", "Pagare", "To pay"],
              "rows": [
                ["(io)", "cerco", "I look for", "(io)", "pago", "I pay"],
                ["(tu)", "cerchi", "you look for", "(tu)", "paghi", "you pay"],
                ["(lui/lei)", "cerca", "he/she/it looks for", "(lui/lei)", "paga", "he/she/it pays"],
                ["(noi)", "cerchiamo", "we look for", "(noi)", "paghiamo", "we pay"],
                ["(voi)", "cercate", "you look for", "(voi)", "pagate", "you pay"],
                ["(loro)", "cercano", "they look for", "(loro)", "pagano", "they pay"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["**Cerchi Marco?**", "Are you looking for Marco?"],
                ["**Giochiamo a pallone.**", "We play football."],
                ["**Perché litighi con tuo fratello?**", "Why are you arguing with your brother?"],
                ["**Paghiamo sempre il conto!**", "We always pay the bill!"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "5.07",
            "content": "Verbs ending in -iare (first conjugation) normally have only one i in the second person singular and the first person plural:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["", "Cominciare", "To start/begin", "", "Mangiare", "To eat"],
              "rows": [
                ["(io)", "comincio", "I begin/start", "(io)", "mangio", "I eat"],
                ["(tu)", "cominci", "you begin/start", "(tu)","mangi", "you eat"],
                ["(lui/lei)", "comincia", "he/she/it begins/starts", "(lui/lei)", "mangia", "he/she/it eats"],
                ["(noi)", "cominciamo", "we begin/start", "(noi)", "mangiamo", "we eat"],
                ["(voi)", "cominciate", "you begin/start", "(voi)", "mangiate", "you eat"],
                ["(loro)", "cominciano", "they begin/start", "(loro)", "mangiano", "they eat"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["**Quando cominci la scuola?**", "When do you start school?"],
                ["**Cominciamo la partita.**", "We’re starting the game."],
                ["**Mangi troppo!**", "You eat too much!"],
                ["**Stasera mangiamo fuori.**", "This evening we’re eating out."]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "5.07",
            "content": "Regular verbs in -ere are conjugated as follows:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Endings", "", "Prendere",  "To take/get"],
              "rows": [
                ["**-o**", "(io)", "prendo", "I take/get"],
                ["**-i**", "(tu)", "prendi", " you take/get"],
                ["**-e**", "(lui/lei)", "prende", " he/she/it takes/gets"],
                ["**-iamo**", "(noi)", "prendiamo", "we take/get"],
                ["**-ete**", "(voi)", "prendete", "you take/get"],
                ["**-ono**", "(loro)", "prendono", "they take/get"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["Prendo il prossimo treno.", "I’m getting/taking the next train."],
                ["Prendiamo questa strada.", " We take this road."],
                ["Anna scrive una lettera.", "Anna is writing a letter."],
                ["Marco e Martina ridono molto.", "Marco and Martina laugh a lot."]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "5.09",
            "content": "Verbs ending in -cere (or -scere) and -gere (or -ggere) change the sound of c (or sc) and g (or -gg), which become ‘hard’ before the endings of the first person singular (-o) and the third person plural (-ono). So care needs to be taken in speaking these verbs:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["", "Vincere", "Spoken like English", "To Win"],
              "rows": [
                ["(io)", "**vinco**", "k", "I win"],
                ["(tu)", "**vinci**", "ch", "you win"],
                ["(lui/lei)", "**vince**", "ch", "he/she/it wins"],
                ["(noi)", "**vinciamo**", "ch", "we win"],
                ["(voi)", "**vincete**", "ch", "you win"],
                ["(loro)", "**vincono**", "k", "they win"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["", "Leggere", "Spoken like English", "To read"],
              "rows": [
                ["(io)", "**leggo**", "g [as in ‘go’]", "I read"],
                ["(tu)", "**leggi**", "j", "you read"],
                ["(lui/lei)", "**legge**", "j", "he/she/it reads"],
                ["(noi)", "**leggiamo**", "j", "we read"],
                ["(voi)", "**leggete**", "j", "you read"],
                ["(loro)", "**leggono**", "g [as in ‘go’]", "they read"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["", "Conoscere", "Spoken like English", "To know"],
              "rows": [
                ["(io)", "conosco", "sk", "I know", "I read"],
                ["(tu)", "conosci", "sh", "you know", "you read"],
                ["(lui/lei)", "conosce", "sh", "he/she/it knows"],
                ["(noi)", "conosciamo", "sh", "we know"],
                ["(voi)", "conoscete", "sh", "you know"],
                ["(loro)", "conoscono", "sk", "they know"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["**Vince sempre.**", "He/she always wins."],
                ["**Non conosco i tuoi genitori.**", "I don’t know your parents."],
                ["**Leggono il giornale.**", "They read the newspaper."],
                ["**Non piango mai.**", "I never cry."]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "5.10",
            "content": "Regular verbs in -ire are conjugated as follows:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Endings", "Partire", "To leave"],
              "rows": [
                ["(io)", "**parto**", "I leave"],
                ["(tu)", "**parti**", "you leave"],
                ["(lui/lei)", "**parte**", "he/she/it leaves"],
                ["(noi)", "**partiamo**", "we leave"],
                ["(voi)", "**partite**", "you leave"],
                ["(loro)", "**partono**", "they leave"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["**Il treno parte alle 8.00.**", "The train leaves at eight."],
                ["**I miei amici partono domani.**", "My friends are leaving tomorrow."],
                ["**Mia sorella dorme.**", " My sister is sleeping/asleep."],
                ["**Tutte le mattine apriamo le finestre.**", "Every morning we open the windows."]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "5.11",
            "content": "Many verbs in **-ire** (e.g. capire (to understand), costruire (to build), finire (to finish/to end), preferire (to prefer), pulire (to clean)) follow a slightly different pattern, adding -isc- before the singular endings and the third person plural:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["Endings", "", "Capire", "To understand"],
              "rows": [
                ["**-isc-o**", "(io)", "**capisco**", "I understand"],
                ["**-isc-i**", "(tu)", "**capisci**", "you understand"],
                ["**-isc-e**", "(lui/lei)", "**capisce**", "he/she/it understands"],
                ["**-iamo**", "(noi)", "**capiamo**", "we understand"],
                ["**-ite**", "(voi)", "**capite**", "you understand"],
                ["**-isc-ono**", "(loro)", "**capiscono**", "they understand"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "There is no way of telling which is the right pattern for a verb in -ire, other than to check in a dictionary.",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["**Marina capisce tutto.**", "Marina understands everything."],
                ["**La lezione finisce alle 13.00.**", "The lesson/class finishes at 1 p.m."],
                ["**Preferisco parlare italiano.**", "I prefer speaking/to speak Italian."]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Present Tense of Some Irregular Verbs",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "5.12",
            "content": "As we saw in Unit 4, the interrogative is formed by adding a question mark at the end of the sentence:",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["**Carla resta a casa?**", "Is Carla staying at home?"],
                ["**Prendi sempre la macchina fotografica?**", "Do you always take the camera?"],
                ["**Quando partite?**", "When are you leaving? "],
                ["**Capisci tutto?**", "Do you understand everything?"]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Negative form",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "5.13",
            "content": "The negative is formed by putting non (not) before the verb:",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["**Non parlo italiano.**", "I don’t speak Italian."],
                ["**Non prendiamo la macchina fotografica.**", "We’re not taking the camera."],
                ["**Giulia e Susanna non partono?**", "Aren’t Giulia and Susanna leaving?"],
                ["**Non capisce niente.**", " He/she doesn’t understand anything."]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Formal form",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "5.14",
            "content": "As we saw in Unit 4, the pronouns used for the formal form are Lei for the singular (for both women and men) and Voi for the plural (the pronoun Loro is much more formal):",
            "table": {
              "rows": [
                ["**(Lei) Parla italiano?**", "Do you speak Italian?"],
                ["**Non prende un taxi, Professor Masi?**", "Aren’t you taking a taxi, Professor Masi?"],
                ["** Partite, Signori Bianco?**", "Are you leaving (Mr and Mrs Bianco)?"],
                ["**((Loro) Partono, Signori Bianco?)**", "Are you leaving (Mr and Mrs Bianco)?"]
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Present tense of some irregular verbs",
        "paragraphs": [
          {
            "id": "5.15",
            "content":  "In Italian, as in most languages, there are a number of irregular verbs whose conjugation is best learned by heart and with use. Here is the conjugation of some of the more frequently used irregular verbs:",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["", "Dare", "Stare", "Sapere", "Andare", "Uscire", "Venire"],
              "rows": [
                ["", "Give", "Stay/Live/Feel", "Know", "Go", "Go Out/Leave", "Come"],
                ["(io)", "dò", "sto", "so", "vado", "esco", "vengo"],
                ["(tu)", "dai", "stai", "sai", "vai", "esci", "vieni"],
                ["(lui/lei)", "dà", "sta", "sa", "va", "esce", "viene"],
                ["(noi)", "diamo", "stiamo", "sappiamo", "andiamo", "usciamo", "veniamo"],
                ["(voi)", "date", "state", "sapete", "andate", "uscite", "venite"],
                ["(loro)", "danno", "stanno", "sanno", "vanno", "escono", "vengono"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "",
            "table": {
              "headers": ["", "Dovere", "Dire", "Potere", "Fare", "Volere", "Bere"],
              "rows": [
                ["", "Must/Have To", "Say/Tell", "Can/May/Be Able", "Do/Make", "Wish/Want", "Drink"],
                ["(io)", "devo", "dico", "posso", "faccio", "voglio", "bevo"],
                ["(tu)", "devi", "dici", "puoi", "fai", "vuoi", "bevi"],
                ["(lui/lei)", "deve", "dice", "può", "fa", "vuole", "beve"],
                ["(noi)", "dobbiamo", "diciamo", "possiamo", "facciamo", "vogliamo", "beviamo"],
                ["(voi)", "dovete", "dite", "potete", "fate", "volete", "bevete"],
                ["(loro)", "devono", "dicono", "possono", "fanno", "vogliono", "bevono"]
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "content": "The verb riuscire (to succeed/manage/be able to) follows the same pattern as uscire.",
            "table": {
                "rows": [
                    ["**Cosa fai?**", "What are you doing?"],
                    ["**‘Come stai?’ ‘Sto bene, grazie.’**", "‘How are you?’ ‘I’m fine, thank you.’"],
                    ["**Mia zia sta a Bologna.**", "My aunt lives in Bologna."],
                    ["**Vado al cinema.**", "I’m going to the cinema."],
                    ["**Stasera non esco.**", "I’m not going out tonight."],
                    ["**Domani esco presto.**", "I’m leaving early tomorrow."],
                    ["**Non riesco a capire.**", "I can’t understand."],
                    ["**Non riesco a chiudere la porta.**", "I can’t manage to close the door."],
                    ["**Adesso sapete tutto.**", "Now you know everything.*"]
                ]
            }
          },
            {
                "content": "* It is important not to confuse **sapere** and **conoscere** (paragraph 9). Both mean ‘to know’, but they are not always interchangeable. The basic difference is that **sapere** generally means ‘to know/be aware of/to have knowledge of a fact’ (but see also paragraph 17 below), whereas **conoscere** means ‘to be acquainted/familiar with’, or sometimes ‘to meet/make the acquaintance of’ (e.g. in the expression **piacere di conoscerti**, pleased to meet you). Thus **sapere** is never used for people, and **conoscere** is never followed by a phrase containing a verb:",
                "table": {
                    "rows": [
                        ["**Sappiamo già che c’è sciopero domani.**", "We already know that there is a strike tomorrow."],
                        ["**Sai che ora è?**", "Do you know what time it is?"],
                        ["**Sai perché?**", "Do you know why?"],
                        ["**Non so che cosa fare.**", "I don’t know what to do."],
                        ["**Conosco le regole del gioco.**", "I know the rules of the game."],
                        ["**Ho conosciuto il padre di Pia.**", "I (have) met Pia’s father."],
                        ["**Non conosco il tuo ragazzo.**", "I don’t know your boyfriend."],
                        ["**Conosci questa città?**", "Do you know this town?"]
                    ]
                }
            },
            {
                "id": "5.16",
                "content": "Dovere, potere and volere usually need to be followed by another verb in the infinitive:",
                "table": {
                    "rows": [
                        ["**Dobbiamo fare gli esercizi.**", "We’ve got to do the exercises."],
                        ["**Posso parlare con Luigi?**", "May I talk to Luigi?"],
                        ["**Puoi telefonare domani.**", "You can phone tomorrow."],
                        ["**Non vogliono uscire.**", "They don’t want to go out."]
                    ]
                }

            },
            {
                "id": "5.17",
                "content": "The verb sapere is another that is often followed by a verb in the infinitive; used in this way, it expresses the ability to do something (in the sense of ‘to know how to’ do something):",
                "table": {
                    "rows": [
                        ["**So nuotare.**", "I can swim. [i.e. I know how to]"],
                        ["**Paolo non sa ballare.**", "Paolo can’t dance. [i.e. he doesn’t know how to]"],
                        ["**Sai usare quello scanner?**", "Can you/Do you know how to use that scanner?"]
                    ]
                }
            },
            {
                "id": "5.18",
                "content": "A few verbs end in -urre (like condurre (to lead/drive/manage), tradurre (to translate), produrre (to produce), etc.); all have the following pattern:",
                "table": {
                    "headers": ["Endings", "", "**Produrre**", "To produce"],
                    "rows": [
                        ["**-uc-o**", "io", "**produco**", "I produce"],
                        ["**-uc-i**", "tu", "**produci**", "you produce"],
                        ["**-uc-e**", "lui/lei", "**produce**", "he/she/it produces"],
                        ["**-uc-iamo**", "noi", "**produciamo**", "we produce"],
                        ["**-uc-ete**", "voi", "**producete**", "you produce"],
                        ["**-uc-ono**", "loro", "**producono**", "they produce"]
                    ]
                }
            },
            {
                "content": "",
                "table": {
                    "rows": [
                        ["**Questa fabbrica produce automobili.**", "This factory produces cars."],
                        ["**Traducono dal francese.**", "They translate from French."]
                    ]
                }
            }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  "exercises": [
    {
      "title": "Exercise 1",
      "instruction": "Supply the present tense of the verb in brackets.",
      "examples": ["Non (io conoscere) tua mamma: conosco"],
      "items": [
        {"question": "Claudio (arrivare) con il prossimo treno.", "answer": "arriva"},
        {"question": "Anna (vivere) a Roma.", "answer": "vive"},
        {"question": "Non (noi mangiare) spesso fuori.", "answer": "mangiamo"},
        {"question": "(tu cercare) casa?", "answer": "cerchi"},
        {"question": "Stasera (voi prendere) l’autobus.", "answer": "prendete"},
        {"question": "Il treno di Giorgio (partire) alle 18.", "answer": "parte"},
        {"question": "Tutti i giorni (noi leggere) il giornale.", "answer": "leggiamo"},
        {"question": "(tu pulire) il bagno?", "answer": "pulisci"},
        {"question": "(io conoscere) molti italiani.", "answer": "conosco"},
        {"question": "I giochi (finire) sempre alle 17.", "answer": "finiscono"},
        {"question": "Non (noi guidare) l’auto.", "answer": "guidiamo"},
        {"question": "Anna e io (giocare) a carte.", "answer": "giochiamo"},
        {"question": "Perché non (voi tornare) in Scozia?", "answer": "tornate"},
        {"question": "Non (tu capire) nulla!", "answer": "capisci"},
        {"question": "Giorgio e Paola non (spendere) molto.", "answer": "spendono"},
        {"question": "Dove (Lei abitare), Signor Verdi?", "answer": "abita"},
        {"question": "(Voi pagare) l’affitto, Signori Rossi?", "answer": "pagate"},
        {"question": "(tu viaggiare) molto.", "answer": "viaggi"},
        {"question": "Non (tu ricevere) molte lettere?", "answer": "ricevi"},
        {"question": "Piero e Gianni (lasciare) il cane a casa.", "answer": "lasciano"}
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Exercise 2",
      "instruction": "Supply the present tense of the verb in brackets.",
      "examples": ["(io bere) molta acqua: bevo"],
      "items": [
        {"question": "Stasera (loro) andare al cinema.", "answer": "vanno"},
        {"question": "La nostra fabbrica (produrre) pasta.", "answer": "produce"},
        {"question": "Domani (noi dare) una festa.", "answer": "diamo"},
        {"question": "(tu andare) spesso in spiaggia?", "answer": "vai"},
        {"question": "(voi fare) gli esercizi?", "answer": "fate"},
        {"question": "Non (noi riuscire) a capire.", "answer": "riusciamo"},
        {"question": "(voi venire) a casa?", "answer": "venite"},
        {"question": "Non (io potere) uscire oggi.", "answer": "posso"},
        {"question": "(loro volere) dormire.", "answer": "vogliono"},
        {"question": "(tu dire) la verità?", "answer": "dici"},
        {"question": "Tu e Claudia (potere) partire.", "answer": "potete"},
        {"question": "(io volere) studiare.", "answer": "voglio"},
        {"question": "Dove (tu stare) adesso?", "answer": "stai"},
